# A nuclear family — the smallest complete Kul document worth reading.
#
# Two people marry; two children are born to that marriage. This is the
# classical descendency tree at its simplest: a couple joined by a
# marriage edge, with their children hanging from the midpoint of that
# edge one generation below.
#
# Everything Kul does is built on the three constructs shown here:
#   - `person`   declares someone (a `name:` and `gender:` are required;
#                every other field is optional and renders as absence).
#   - `marriage` joins two people; the first-listed spouse is the *host*.
#   - `birth`    (a sub-statement, indented under a person) says which
#                marriage a person was born to — the parent link.

# ---- The couple ----
person hiroshi  name:"Hiroshi Tanaka"  gender:male    born:1978-02-11
person yuki     name:"Yuki Tanaka"     gender:female  born:1980-06-30

marriage m_hiroshi_yuki hiroshi yuki  start:2005-09-20

# ---- Their children (born to m_hiroshi_yuki) ----
# Each child's `birth` names the marriage, not the parents — children
# attach to the marriage edge, matching how the data is written.
person akiko  name:"Akiko Tanaka"  gender:female  born:2008-04-17
  birth m_hiroshi_yuki

person kenji  name:"Kenji Tanaka"  gender:male  born:2011-11-03
  birth m_hiroshi_yuki
